[{"id":31620,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$288 \\mathrm{pm}$","$398 \\mathrm{pm}$","$618 \\mathrm{pm}$","$144 \\mathrm{pm}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"For an ionic substance in FCC arrangement,\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& 2\\left(r^{+}+r^{-}\\right)=\\text {edge length } \\\\\n& 2\\left(110+r^{-}\\right)=508 \\\\\n& r^{-}=144 \\mathrm{pm}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":31586,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AgBr</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>CsCl</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KBr</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ZnS</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AgBr</mi></math> can exhibit both Schottky and Frenkel defect.</p><p>Schottky&nbsp;defect&nbsp;in&nbsp;<em><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AgBr</mi></math></em>&nbsp;is exhibited due to the precipitation of both cations and anions. In&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>AgBr</mi></math>,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Ag</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math>&nbsp;ion is small in size and when removed&nbsp;from the lattice point, they can occupy the interstitial sites and, hence,&nbsp;shows&nbsp;both Frenkel and Schottky&nbsp;defects.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (08 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31608,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$157 \\mathrm{~pm}$","$128 \\mathrm{~pm}$","$108 \\mathrm{~pm}$","$181 \\mathrm{~pm}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"For FCC,\n$r=\\frac{\\sqrt{2} a}{4}=\\frac{a}{2 \\sqrt{2}}=0.3535 a$\ngiven $a=361 \\mathrm{~pm}$\n$\\begin{aligned}\nr & =0.3535 \\times 361 \\\\\n& =128 \\mathrm{~pm}\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (25 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":31585,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Density =&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>Volume</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>27</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>27</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>05</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=4&#160;&#160;&#8658;</mo><mi>fcc</mi></math>&nbsp;unit cell</p><p>For&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>fcc</mi></math>&nbsp;</p><p>unit cell&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>414</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>405</mn></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>143</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1675</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>pm</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>143</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>17</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>pm</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (03 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31544,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><msup><mi>Cs</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><msup><mi>Cl</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><msup><mi>Cs</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><msup><mi>Cl</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><msup><mi>Cs</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><msup><mi>Cl</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><msup><mi>Cs</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><msup><mi>Cl</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></msub><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>CsCl</mi></math>&nbsp;has body centered type structure in which <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Cs</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math> occupies at corner of a cube and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Cl</mi><mo>&#8211;</mo></msup></math> occupies the centre of the cube.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><msup><mi>Cs</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><msup><mi>Cl</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></msub><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math>&nbsp;(where a is the edge length of&nbsp;the cube)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><msup><mi>Cs</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mi>Cr</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (15 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31574,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Ionic solid","Molecular solid","Metallic solid","Covalent solid"],"answer":3,"solution":"Covalent or network solid have very high melting point, and&nbsp;they are insulators in their solid and molten form.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31594,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Hexagonal","Monoclinic","Triclinic","Tetragonal"],"answer":2,"solution":"The most inorganized system has <math><mi>a</mi><mo>≠</mo><mi>b</mi><mo>≠</mo><mi>c</mi></math> and <math><mi>α</mi><mo>≠</mo><mi>β</mi><mo>≠</mo><mi>γ</mi><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mn>90</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>o</mi></mrow></msup></math> is called the triclinic system.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31579,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>If number of lattice points are <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math>.</p><p>then effective octahedral voids <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi></math></p><p>So, octahedral voids / lattice site <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31567,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Both Statement I and Statement II are true"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>A Frenkel defect is another form of a point defect which is created when an atom or cation leaves its original place in the lattice structure to create a vacancy while occupying another interstitial position within the solid crystal.&nbsp;Frenkel defect is dislocation defect, it is not interstitial defect, and it is not responsible for colour of solid.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Aug Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31547,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math> and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<blockquote><p>A face-centered cubic (fcc) unit cell contains a component in the center of each face in addition to those at the corners of the cube. The atoms touch each other along the face diagonal.</p><p>For <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>FCC</mi><mo>:</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math></p><p>A body-centered cubic (bcc) unit cell contains a component in the center of the cube&nbsp;in addition to those at the corners of the cube.&nbsp;The atoms touch each other along the body&nbsp;diagonal.<br /><br />For <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>BCC</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>:</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31559,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Schottky defect decreases the density of the substance.","Frenkel defect does not alter the density of the substance.","Interstitial defect increases the density of the substance.","Vacancy defect increases the density of the substance."],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>Frenkel Defect: This defect is shown by ionic solids. The smaller ion (usually cation) is dislocated from its normal site to an interstitial site. It creates a vacancy defect at its original site and an interstitial defect at its new location. Frenkel defect is also called dislocation defect. It does not change the density of the solid. In all other defects there is a change in the density.</p><p>In Schottky defect equal number of cation and anion are missing from their position so, it&nbsp;decreases the density of the substance.</p><p>In Interstitial defect extra atoms are present at interstitial position so, it&nbsp;increases the density of the substance.</p><p>Due to vacancy defect density of the substance will decrease. since atoms are missing from their positions.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31623,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$X_4 Y_3$","$X_2 Y_3$","$X_2 Y$","$\\mathrm{X}_3 \\mathrm{Y}_4$"],"answer":0,"solution":"No. of atoms of $Y=4$\nNo. of atoms of $X=\\frac{2}{3} \\times 8$\nFormula of compound will be $X_4 Y_3$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2008","image":null},{"id":31558,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math> is body centred cubic, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p><p>Let mass of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>&nbsp;atom of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></math> is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p><p>Edge length&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>300</mn><mi>pm</mi></math></p><p>Density&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi>cm</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi>cm</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>300</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>27</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>24</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>81</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>24</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></math></p><p>Atoms of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>T</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>t</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>l</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>s</mi><mi>s</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>M</mi><mi>a</mi><mi>s</mi><mi>s</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>o</mi><mi>f</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>o</mi><mi>n</mi><mi>e</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>a</mi><mi>t</mi><mi>o</mi><mi>m</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfrac><mn>180</mn><mrow><mn>81</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>24</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>22</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>22</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup><mo>&#8773;</mo><mn>22</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31568,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi></mfenced><mtext>&#160;only&#160;</mtext></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math> only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math> only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>)</mo></math> only"],"answer":3,"solution":"(A) Crystalline solids have definite arrangement of constituent particles and have long range order.<br />(C), (D) Different constituent particles of an amorphous solid have different bond strengths and soften over a range of temperatures.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31626,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Frenkel defect","Frenkel and Schottky defects","Interstitial defect","Schottky defect"],"answer":3,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":31596,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Tridymite","Quartz","Amorphous silica","Mica"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Piezoelectric materials are those that produce an electric current when placed under mechanical stress.</p><p>Quartz is used as a piezoelectric material in electronic devices.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31550,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The density of the crystal lattice can be calculated as follows,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo></math>effective number of atoms in unit cell(For BCC=2 and FCC=4)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo></math>Molar mass</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub></math>=Avogadro&#39;s number</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo></math>Edge length</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>FCC</mi></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>BCC</mi></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">w</mi></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">w</mi></msub></mrow><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>90</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31549,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>XY</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Atoms of Element&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi></math>, are present in cubic close packing. In cubic close packing the number of atoms per unit cell is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math>.</p><p class=\"Solution_html__KkUW2\" style=\"border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: start; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;\">So, the effective number of element&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi></math>,&nbsp;per unit cell is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn></math></p><p class=\"Solution_html__KkUW2\" style=\"border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: start; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;\">Element&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></math>, are present at one third of the tetrahedral voids.</p><p class=\"Solution_html__KkUW2\" style=\"border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: start; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;\">Number of tetrahedral void&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo></math>Twice the number of atoms in unit cell</p><p class=\"Solution_html__KkUW2\" style=\"border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: start; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;\">Number of atoms of Element <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi></math>&nbsp;are present&nbsp;unit cell&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>8</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math></p><p class=\"Solution_html__KkUW2\" style=\"border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: start; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>:</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mfrac><mn>8</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>:</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>:</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace></math></p><p class=\"Solution_html__KkUW2\" style=\"border: 0px; margin: 0px; padding: 0px; text-align: start; -webkit-text-stroke-width: 0px;\">Formula of the compound&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (06 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31553,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The density of the crystal can be calculated as follows,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>density</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>effective</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>number</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>atoms</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>Molar</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mass</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>Avogadro</mi><mo>&#39;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>number</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>Edge</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>length</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>72</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>125</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>24</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>166</mn><mo>&#8771;</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31592,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$0.0432 \\mathrm{~kg} \\mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$","$0.0216 \\mathrm{~kg} \\mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$","$0.0305 \\mathrm{~kg} \\mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$","$0.4320 \\mathrm{~kg} \\mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Density $=\\frac{Z \\times M}{N_{A} \\times a^{3}}$\r\n\r\n$9 \\times 10^{3}=\\frac{4 \\times \\mathrm{M}}{\\left(200 \\times \\sqrt{2} \\times 10^{-12}\\right)^{3} 6 \\times 10^{23}}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (11 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31613,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Density of crystals remains unaffected due to Frenkel defect.","In BCC unit cell the void space is $32 \\%$.","Density of crystals decreases due to Schottky defect.","Electrical conductivity of semiconductors and metals increases with increase in temperature."],"answer":3,"solution":"The electrical resistance of metals depends upon temperature. Electrical resistance decreases with decrease in temperature and becomes zero near the absolute temperature. Material in this state is said to possess super conductivity.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (26 May Online)","image":null},{"id":31584,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>40</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>For BCC&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mtext>&#160;Volume&#160;</mtext></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>17</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>17</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>50</mn></math></p><p>No. of mole <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>200</mn><mn>50</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p><p>No. of molecule <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (05 Sep Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31624,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$\\frac{20}{3} \\pi r^3$","$\\frac{24}{3} \\pi r^3$","$\\frac{12}{3} \\pi r^3$","$\\frac{16}{3} \\pi r^3$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} V & =n \\times\\left(\\frac{4}{3} \\pi r^3\\right) \\\\ & =4 \\times\\left(\\frac{4}{3} \\pi r^3\\right) \\\\ & =\\frac{16}{3} \\pi r^3\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2006","image":null},{"id":31555,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>XY</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>The share of the atom present at corner of the cube is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>8</mn></math>. The share of the atom at face centre is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo></math>&nbsp;Hence, the molecule can be represented as follows,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>8</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msub><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></msub><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></msub><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math>(Empirical formula)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">X</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#160;&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Y</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (25 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31593,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<p>HCP lattice - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math>tetrahedral voids - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p>","<p>HCP lattice - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math> tetrahedral voids - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>&nbsp;</p>","<p>HCP lattice - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math> tetrahedral voids - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p>","<p>HCP lattice - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math>&nbsp;tetrahedral voids - <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math></p>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Atom <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> forms HCP&nbsp;as&nbsp;anions are larger in size.</p><p>From the formula&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>,</p><p>Number of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math> atoms<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math>,</p><p>Then, number of tetrahedral voids&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo></math>Tetrahedral voids<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn></math>.</p><p>As <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>'</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>'</mo></math>&nbsp;is occupying tetrahedral voids,</p><p>&nbsp;<math> <mrow> <mfrac> <mn>1</mn> <mn>3</mn> </mfrac> </mrow> </math>&nbsp;of&nbsp;tetrahedral voids<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math><br /><br />Therefore, formula of the compound<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31606,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A<sub>2</sub>B<sub>3</sub>","AB<sub>2</sub>","A<sub>5</sub>B<sub>2</sub>","A<sub>2</sub>B<sub>5</sub>"],"answer":3,"solution":"A atoms at corners&nbsp;<math> <mrow> <mo>=</mo> <mn>8</mn> <mo>&#215;</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mn>8</mn> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mo>&#160;A (one atom)</mo> </mrow> </math><br /><br />B atom is missing at One face centre then will present at 5 faces<br /><br />At face centre atom contribute 1/2 part<br /><br />Number of B atom at Face centre = <math> <mrow> <mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac> <mn>1</mn> <mn>2</mn> </mfrac> </mrow> </math> (B atom)<br /><br />So formula of compound = <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (09 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":31610,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["Coordination number in bcc mode of packing is 8 .","Coordination number in hep mode of packing is 12 .","Void space in hcp mode of packing is $32 \\%$.","Void space in ccp mode of packing is $26 \\%$."],"answer":2,"solution":"The $h c p$ arrangement of atoms occupies $74 \\%$ of the available space and thus has $26 \\%$ vacant space.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (22 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":31619,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{AB}_2$","$A_2 B_3$","$\\mathrm{A}_2 \\mathrm{~B}_5$","$A_2 B$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Effective no.of $A$ atoms $=\\frac{1}{8} \\times 8=1$\nEffective no.of $B$ atoms $=\\frac{1}{2} \\times 5$ (One is missing) $=\\frac{5}{2}$\nTherefore formula is $A_1 B_{\\frac{5}{2}}=A_2 B_5$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2011","image":null},{"id":31580,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"FCC,<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>63</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>54</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>1000</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>022</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>596</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>9076</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>kg</mi><mo>/</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (25 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31577,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCP</mi></math> structure : Per atom, there will be one octahedral void <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>OV</mi><mo>)</mo></math> and two tetrahedral voids <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi>TV</mi><mo>)</mo></math>.</p><p>Therefore, total three voids per atom are present in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>HCP</mi></math> structure.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo></math>&nbsp;Therefore total no. of atoms of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Ga</mi></math>&nbsp;will be-</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Mass</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Molar</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Mass</mi><mo>&#160;</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>581</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>70</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">g</mi><mo>/</mo><mi>mol</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>023</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8594;</mo></math> Now, total Number of voids <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#215;</mo></math> total no. of atoms&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>581</mn></mrow><mn>70</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>023</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>99</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>21</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8771;</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>21</mn></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (16 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31590,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>","<math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"For ccp structure: <br/>Number of octahedral voids are <math><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math>  <br/>Number of tetrahedral voids are <math><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn></math>  <br/><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math> (number of atoms present in ccp structure) <br/><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>  <br/><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn></math>  <br/>So formula is <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>8</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></msub><mo>.</mo></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31545,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Edge length of the unit cell <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p>Radius of sodium atom <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>)</mo><mo>=</mo><mo>?</mo></math></p><p>Since, sodium&nbsp;crystallises in body&nbsp;centered cubic arrangement.</p><p>The radius of the atom and the edge length of the cubic unit cell are related as follows,</p><p>For bcc structure,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msqrt><mn>3</mn></msqrt><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>732</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>732</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>17</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>3</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#197;</mi></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (13 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":31563,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>For&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NaCl</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math>&nbsp;and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>58</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math>&nbsp;gram</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>Volume</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>43</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>58</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi></mfenced><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>58</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>43</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>23</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>23</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>9</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>24</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>08</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math></p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/df4167f2-5974-40eb-b280-47e3a0ede258-image.png\" style=\"width: 350px; height: 217px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mrow><msup><mi>Na</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>+</mo><msup><mi>Cl</mi><mo>-</mo></msup></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>08</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8771;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31581,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>All the corner atoms around&nbsp;body centre atom are nearest to that atom, so co-ordination number in this structure is eight.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (24 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":31546,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Solid State","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>The density of crystal can be calculated as follows,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#961;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#961;</mi><mo>=</mo></math>density of the unit cell</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo></math>Effective atomic number</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">M</mi><mo>=</mo></math>Molar mass</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo></math>Avogadro&#39;s number</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">a</mi><mo>=</mo></math>Edge length of the unit cell</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>23</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>3</mn><msup><mo>)</mo><mn>3</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>24</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">Z</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>02</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>27</mn></mrow><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (11 Apr Shift 1)","image":null}]